text:
For reference, the earth being round was something that had generally been figured out before the Roman Empire was a thing. 

You basically have to live somewhere that is both very flat and heavily forrested to not have observable, measurable things that prove the earth isn't flat.  Because otherwise there are places you can stand where you can just straight up See the curve of the horrizon, or things appearing 'over the edge'. It's particularly noticeable at sea, where the 'top' of ships (or structures on land if you're approaching) appear before the rest of them, which would not happen if they were just getting larger as you got closer, rather than ceasing to be obstructed by the 'flat' sea. 

It gets a bit more complicated in other places, but you can do the same thing with a large flat area of grassland and a structure or rock formation of decent size.   And there's some other thing you can do with shadows and digging holes in a north/south line? I forget how that works.

Yes, they have different... overtones? - for some... phonemes? - but not all. So if you're not looking, and there was some silence, and there's a short phrase with timbre that fits both, you get startled. Even with decent headphones with normal tuning.

But for their catchphrases, that mostly doesn't work, especially because we were trained on those a lot more. But that's what they were "testing" on, not on random barks. text:
Perception of sound is complicated (see: audiophiles). There were decades of studies, we got Harman research, and things still changed even this year. A completely uncontrolled stream with technical issues, with "researchers" with no education in music or sound nor experience in experimental science, and the goal to entertain and not find the specific circumstances that do produce similarities that so many people notice, is no "proof" for anyone. It's just entertainment.

I use a variety of good headphones and earphones, and I called the similarities in Mumei's debut stream. I've been watching EN almost since beginning. And I still stumbled upon this soundalike again a couple days ago. There are circumstances to this, they are vague until you do proper research, but catchphrases and intentional imitation aren't it.
